---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import FolkArtBorder from '../components/FolkArtBorder.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Who's Who in the Gita — Gita Kids" description="Meet the main characters of the Bhagavad Gita — kings, warriors, teachers, and the Divine himself.">
  <div class="max-w-reading mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="text-center mb-16">
      <span class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold">Before You Begin</span>
      <h1 class="font-body text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-3 mb-4">Who's Who in the Gita</h1>
      <p class="font-body text-base text-gray-600 max-w-md mx-auto leading-relaxed">
        Before you begin, meet the people whose story you are about to read.
        Some are heroes. Some are flawed. All of them are searching for what is right.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- The Central Pair -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
        <h2 class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold whitespace-nowrap">The Central Pair</h2>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Krishna -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(26, 104, 71, 0.1); border: 2px solid #1A6847;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #1A6847;">कृ</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold" style="color: #1A6847;">Krishna</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg" style="color: #1A6847; opacity: 0.7;">कृष्णः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2" style="color: #1A6847;">The Divine Teacher &middot; Pandava Side</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Krishna is God himself, come to earth in human form. He is Arjuna's charioteer, best friend,
                and guide. With his blue-tinged skin, peacock feather crown, and a flute tucked at his waist,
                he speaks with a gentle smile even on the edge of the most terrible battle the world has ever seen.
                Almost every verse of the Gita is his voice — patient, loving, and wise beyond measure.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>

        <!-- Arjuna -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(184, 92, 58, 0.1); border: 2px solid #B85C3A;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #B85C3A;">अ</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold" style="color: #B85C3A;">Arjuna</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg" style="color: #B85C3A; opacity: 0.7;">अर्जुनः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2" style="color: #B85C3A;">The Warrior Prince &middot; Pandava Side</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Arjuna is the finest archer in the world, lean and athletic, with his legendary bow Gandiva
                always at his side. He is brave, kind, and deeply honourable. But when the battle is about
                to begin and he sees his own family on the other side, he is overcome with doubt and grief.
                His questions to Krishna become the Bhagavad Gita.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Kaurava Side -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
        <h2 class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold whitespace-nowrap">The Kaurava Side</h2>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Dhritarashtra -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(107, 114, 128, 0.1); border: 2px solid #6B7280;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #6B7280;">धृ</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold" style="color: #6B7280;">Dhritarashtra</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg" style="color: #6B7280; opacity: 0.7;">धृतराष्ट्रः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2" style="color: #6B7280;">The Blind King &middot; Kaurava Side</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Dhritarashtra is the elderly king of Hastinapura and father of the hundred Kauravas.
                Born blind, he wears a silk blindfold and sits on his throne while others describe the
                world to him. He loves his sons but cannot bring himself to correct them. The Gita begins
                with his anxious question: "What did my sons and the Pandavas do on the battlefield?"
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>

        <!-- Duryodhana -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(146, 64, 14, 0.1); border: 2px solid #92400E;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #92400E;">दु</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold" style="color: #92400E;">Duryodhana</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg" style="color: #92400E; opacity: 0.7;">दुर्योधनः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2" style="color: #92400E;">The Eldest Kaurava Prince &middot; Kaurava Side</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Duryodhana is Dhritarashtra's eldest son — proud, strong-jawed, and ambitious,
                dressed in red-gold armour with an ornate crown. He refused to give the Pandavas even
                five villages of land, and his jealousy drove the two families to war. In the Gita's
                opening, he surveys both armies and tries to bolster his own confidence.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Great Elders -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
        <h2 class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold whitespace-nowrap">The Great Elders</h2>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Bhishma -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(107, 114, 128, 0.1); border: 2px solid #9CA3AF;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #6B7280;">भी</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold text-gray-800">Bhishma</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg text-gray-500">भीष्मः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-gray-500 mb-2">The Grandsire &middot; Kaurava Commander (by duty, not by heart)</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Bhishma is the great-grandfather of both the Pandavas and the Kauravas, an ancient
                warrior of towering stature with flowing white hair and a massive bow. He took a
                legendary vow of lifelong celibacy so his father could remarry, and he has protected
                the kingdom ever since. He fights on the Kaurava side because of his oath to the throne,
                even though his heart aches for the Pandavas.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>

        <!-- Drona -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(199, 91, 18, 0.1); border: 2px solid #C75B12;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #C75B12;">द्रो</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold text-gray-800">Drona</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg text-gray-500">द्रोणः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-gray-500 mb-2">The Teacher of Warriors &middot; Kaurava Commander (by obligation)</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Dronacharya is the guru who taught both the Pandavas and the Kauravas the art of war.
                An elderly sage in saffron robes, he carries a teaching staff and a bow with equal
                authority. Arjuna was his favourite student. Like Bhishma, he stands on the Kaurava
                side out of loyalty to the throne that gave him his livelihood — one of the story's
                deepest tragedies.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Pandava Brothers -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
        <h2 class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold whitespace-nowrap">The Pandava Family</h2>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Draupadi -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(199, 91, 18, 0.1); border: 2px solid #C75B12;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #C75B12;">द्रौ</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold text-gray-800">Draupadi</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg text-gray-500">द्रौपदी</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-gray-500 mb-2">The Queen of the Pandavas &middot; Pandava Side</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Draupadi is the wife of all five Pandava brothers and a queen of extraordinary courage.
                Born from sacred fire, she endured public humiliation when the Kauravas tried to disrobe
                her in court — and it was Krishna who protected her. Her suffering and her fierce call for
                justice are among the reasons this war could not be avoided.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>

        <!-- The Other Pandava Brothers -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(184, 92, 58, 0.1); border: 2px solid #B85C3A;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #B85C3A;">पा</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold text-gray-800">The Other Pandava Brothers</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-gray-500 mb-2">Pandava Side</p>
              <div class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-3">
                <p>
                  Arjuna is one of five brothers. Together they are the <strong class="text-saffron">Pandavas</strong>,
                  sons of King Pandu. You will meet them in the stories throughout this book:
                </p>
                <ul class="space-y-2 ml-1">
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-saffron font-bold mt-0.5">&bull;</span>
                    <span><strong>Yudhishthira</strong> <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-gray-500">(युधिष्ठिरः)</span> — the eldest, known for his truthfulness and righteousness. He is the one who gambled away the kingdom.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-saffron font-bold mt-0.5">&bull;</span>
                    <span><strong>Bhima</strong> <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-gray-500">(भीमः)</span> — the second-born, immensely strong, a mighty warrior with a lion's roar and a tender heart for those he loves.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-saffron font-bold mt-0.5">&bull;</span>
                    <span><strong>Nakula</strong> <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-gray-500">(नकुलः)</span> — the fourth brother, famed for his beauty and his skill with horses and swords.</span>
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-saffron font-bold mt-0.5">&bull;</span>
                    <span><strong>Sahadeva</strong> <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-gray-500">(सहदेवः)</span> — the youngest, quiet and wise, gifted with knowledge of the stars and the future.</span>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The Narrator -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
        <h2 class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-gold whitespace-nowrap">The Narrator</h2>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/40 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Sanjaya -->
        <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start gap-4">
            <div class="flex-shrink-0">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-2xl" style="background-color: rgba(45, 58, 135, 0.1); border: 2px solid #2D3A87;">
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari" style="color: #2D3A87;">सं</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
                <h3 class="font-body text-xl font-bold" style="color: #2D3A87;">Sanjaya</h3>
                <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-lg" style="color: #2D3A87; opacity: 0.7;">सञ्जयः</span>
              </div>
              <p class="font-ui text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-2" style="color: #2D3A87;">The One Who Sees &middot; Neutral</p>
              <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                Sanjaya is Dhritarashtra's trusted minister and charioteer. The sage Vyasa granted
                him a miraculous gift: the ability to see everything happening on the distant
                battlefield as if he were standing right there. He narrates the entire Gita to the
                blind king, describing not just the events but the emotions, the divine visions,
                and even the words spoken in whispers between Krishna and Arjuna.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </FolkArtBorder>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- How to spot who's speaking -->
    <FolkArtBorder style="madhubani" class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="font-body text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How to spot who is speaking</h2>
      <p class="font-body text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        As you read each verse, you will see a coloured tag showing who is speaking.
        Each speaker has their own colour, so you always know whose voice you are hearing:
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full text-sm font-ui font-semibold text-white" style="background-color: #1A6847;">Krishna</span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full text-sm font-ui font-semibold text-white" style="background-color: #B85C3A;">Arjuna</span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full text-sm font-ui font-semibold text-white" style="background-color: #2D3A87;">Sanjaya</span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full text-sm font-ui font-semibold text-white" style="background-color: #6B7280;">Dhritarashtra</span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-full text-sm font-ui font-semibold text-white" style="background-color: #92400E;">Duryodhana</span>
      </div>
    </FolkArtBorder>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <div class="text-center">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/30 to-transparent"></div>
        <span lang="sa" class="font-devanagari text-gold/50 text-lg">&#x0965;</span>
        <div class="flex-1 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-gold/30 to-transparent"></div>
      </div>
      <p class="font-body text-gray-600 mb-6">
        Now that you know the people, step onto the battlefield.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/chapters/01-arjuna-vishada-yoga"
        class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-saffron text-white font-ui text-sm font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-saffron/90 transition-colors"
      >
        Begin Chapter 1 &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
